<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. Description of the Country around Lakes Superior and Huron, 1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0018</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">being found near the Surface of the Earth<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">From Whitefish point to Grand Marais or the Great Marsh is fifteen leagues the course nearly South by West<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The beach all the way nothing but Sand and gravel and the bank which is from twenty to fifty feet high is a continued line of Firs of different kinds.  About thirty years ago the Grand Marais was really what its name indicates; there was a little River Ran through it which Scarsely admitted a Canoe<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  But it is now a beautiful Bason of Water upwards of a league Round, very deep in the middle but rendered useless from a gravel bank which bars the entrance; and tho it has Sometimes from 4 to 6 feet water I have often in several places seen <span class="DelHand-author">it</span> <span class="AddHand-author">the gravel</span> thrown up two or three feet above water<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The entrance is very Remarkable having a high Sand bank to the north east and an equally high bank of Clay to the South West, <span class="DelHand-author">The entrance</span> it is a good half league over and is always deepest off the Southwest point<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Above the Clay bank there is a fine Maple grove Which Runs nearly South but narrows off to the South West where it is lost <span class="DelHand-author">o</span><span class="AddHand-author">i</span>n a deep fissure the Sides of which are covered with Pine and Cedar, on climbing up the opposite Side you are struck with wonder and Surprise on finding Yourself arrived at <span class="DelHand-author">on</span><span class="AddHand-author">a</span> <span class="DelHand-author">Steril</span> sandy plain of Several leagues in extent the side of which</p>

